%S A397571 3,4,13,10,25,16,37,22,28,61,73,40,85,46,52,58,121,133,70,145,157,82,
%T A397571 88,193,100,205,106,217,112,253,130,136,277,148,301,313,325,166,172,
%U A397571 178,361,190,385,196,397,421,445,226,457,232,238,481,250,256,262,268,541,553,280
%N A397571 Field trace Tr_{Q(zeta_p)/Q}(T_p(zeta_p)) of the p-term truncation of Ramanujan's third-order mock theta function f(q) at a primitive p-th root of unity, where p = prime(n+1).
%C A397571 Let p be the n-th odd prime, so p = prime(n+1), and let zeta_p = exp(2*Pi*i/p).
%C A397571 Define T_p(z) = Sum_{m=0..p-1} z^(m^2)/(-z;z)_m^2, where (-z;z)_m = Product_{j=1..m} (1 + z^j). At z = zeta_p this is the p-term truncation of Ramanujan's third-order mock theta function f(q) = Sum_{m>=0} q^(m^2)/(-q;q)_m^2 (A000025).
%C A397571 T_p(zeta_p) is an algebraic integer in Z[zeta_p]. Indeed, for 1 <= j <= p-1 the factor 1 + zeta_p^j = (1 - zeta_p^(2j))/(1 - zeta_p^j) is a cyclotomic unit, since p is odd and zeta_p^(2j) is again a primitive p-th root of unity; hence every denominator (-zeta_p;zeta_p)_m with m <= p-1 is a unit. a(n) is the field trace Tr_{Q(zeta_p)/Q}(T_p(zeta_p)).
%C A397571 The truncation carries the whole series. At z = zeta_p one has (-z;z)_{m+p} = 2*(-z;z)_m and z^((m+p)^2) = z^(m^2), so the summands satisfy t_{m+p} = t_m/4; the series therefore converges at zeta_p and Sum_{m>=0} zeta_p^(m^2)/(-zeta_p;zeta_p)_m^2 = (4/3)*T_p(zeta_p). So T_p(zeta_p) is a normalized truncation, equal to 3/4 of the series value; the series value itself is not an algebraic integer.
%C A397571 Although T_p(zeta_p) is a nontrivial algebraic integer in Q(zeta_p), its trace collapses to an elementary quantity depending only on p mod 6, governed by the quadratic character (-3/p) attached to Q(sqrt(-3)); thus a simple rational-integer invariant of a non-modular object splits the odd primes into the two classes 6k+1 and 6k+5.
%H A397571 Kathrin Bringmann and Larry Rolen, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1186/s40687-015-0035-8">Radial limits of mock theta functions</a>, Research in the Mathematical Sciences, Vol. 2, No. 1 (2015), Article 17.
%H A397571 Amanda Folsom, Ken Ono, and Robert C. Rhoades, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1017/fmp.2013.3">Mock theta functions and quantum modular forms</a>, Forum of Mathematics, Pi, Vol. 1, Cambridge University Press (2013), e2.
%F A397571 a(n) = (3*p - 2 + p*kronecker(-3,p))/2 where p = prime(n+1), for n >= 2; a(1) = 3.
%F A397571 a(n) = 2*p - 1 if p == 1 (mod 6), and a(n) = p - 1 if p == 5 (mod 6) where p = prime(n+1), for n >= 2.
%e A397571 For n = 1, p = 3: T_3(zeta_3) = 2 + zeta_3, so a(1) = Tr(2 + zeta_3) = 3.
%e A397571 For n = 2, p = 5: T_5(zeta_5) = 2 + zeta_5 + zeta_5^2 + 2*zeta_5^3, so a(2) = 4.
%e A397571 For n = 3, p = 7: T_7(zeta_7) = 3 + zeta_7 + zeta_7^3 + zeta_7^4 + 2*zeta_7^5, so a(3) = 13.
%o A397571 (PARI) a(n) = {my(p=prime(n+1), f=polcyclo(p), z=Mod(x,f), T=Mod(0,f), P=Mod(1,f)); for(m=0, p-1, T += z^(m*m)/P^2; P *= 1 + z^(m+1)); trace(T);}
%o A397571 (SageMath)
%o A397571 def a(n):
%o A397571     if n == 1:
%o A397571         return 3
%o A397571     p = nth_prime(n + 1)
%o A397571     return (3*p - 2 + p*kronecker(-3, p)) // 2
%o A397571 print([a(n) for n in range(1, 60)])
